'''Antje Beitske "Anneke" Mulder-Bakker''' (born 7 April 1940) is a historian at the [[University of Groningen]] who is a specialist in the position of women during the [[Middle Ages]]. She writes mainly in Dutch.<ref name=penn>[http://www.upenn.edu/pennpress/book/14149.html ''Lives of the Anchoresses The Rise of the Urban Recluse in Medieval Europe''.] University of Pennsylvania Press. 24 October 2015.</ref>

==Selected English language publications==
*''The Invention of Saintliness'', [[Routledge]], 2002. {{ISBN|0415267595}}
*''Seeing and Knowing: Women and Learning in Medieval Europe, 1200-1550'', Brepols, 2004. (Medieval Women: Texts and Contexts) {{ISBN|2503514480}}
*''Lives of the Anchoresses: The Rise of the Urban Recluse in Medieval Europe'', (Myra Heerspink Scholz, translator), [[University of Pennsylvania Press]], Philadelphia, 2005. {{ISBN|978-0-8122-3852-5}}<ref name=penn/><ref>[http://www.hermitary.com/bookreviews/mulder-bakker.html BOOK REVIEWS: HOUSE OF HERMITS.] ''Hermitary'', 2006. Retrieved 24 October 2015.</ref>
*''Women and Experience in Later Medieval Writing: Reading the Book of Life'', [[Palgrave Macmillan]], 2009. {{ISBN|9780230602878}}<ref>[http://www.palgrave.com/page/detail/women-and-experience-in-later-medieval-writing-anneke-b-mulderbakker/?sf1=barcode&st1=9780230602878 ''Women and Experience in Later Medieval Writing''.] Palgrave Macmillan. Retrieved 24 October 2015.</ref>

